I was on a flight last week, scrolling through a real estate app on my phone, and the navigation between the listings page and the detail page did this smooth, native-feeling crossfade where the photo seemed to scale and slide into place. I stopped mid-scroll. That was a web app. Not a native app. Not React Native. A web app.
I went home, opened DevTools, and confirmed what I suspected: they were using the View Transitions API. No Framer Motion. No giant animation library. Just the browser doing what the browser has finally, mercifully, been allowed to do.
If you’ve been holding off on View Transitions because cross-browser support was patchy, the wait is over. As of late 2025, same-document transitions are Baseline Newly Available, which means they work in every major browser. Cross-document is in Chrome and Safari, on the roadmap in Firefox. We are, for the first time, in production-safe territory.
This post is the practical view: what View Transitions actually do, the React patterns, what’s still rough, and the case for deleting half your motion library.
what View Transitions actually do
The API gives the browser a “before” snapshot and an “after” snapshot of your page, and it animates between them. Crossfade by default. With one line of CSS, you can name specific elements and the browser will morph them between snapshots, which is how you get the shared-element animations that used to require Framer Motion.
The whole API is one function:
document.startViewTransition(() => {
// do the DOM mutation that changes the page
router.push('/profile');
});That’s it. Before the callback runs, the browser screenshots the page. The callback updates the DOM. The browser screenshots again. It crossfades between them. With zero additional CSS you get a free crossfade between any two states.
If you’ve ever written page transition code with Framer Motion’s AnimatePresence, you know the amount of ceremony that previously required: layout animation wrappers, exit propagation, presence flags, key management, hours of debugging why an element flashed. View Transitions does the same thing in one function call.
the shared-element trick
The thing that makes the API actually exciting (versus “yeah, crossfades are nice”): named transitions.
.product-image {
view-transition-name: product-image;
}When the browser screenshots before and after, any element with a view-transition-name is tracked as its own thing. If the same name appears in both snapshots, the browser morphs it: scales, translates, fades, whatever's needed to get from old position to new position.
This is the photo-sliding-into-place effect from the real estate app. The thumbnail on the listings page has view-transition-name: hero-photo. The big image on the detail page has the same name. You navigate. The browser animates the photo from thumb to hero without any JS. Magic.
<!-- listings page -->
<img class="thumb" src="/photo.jpg" style="view-transition-name: hero-photo" /><!-- detail page -->
<img class="hero" src="/photo.jpg" style="view-transition-name: hero-photo" />The names have to be unique per snapshot (no two thumbnails on the listings page can both be hero-photo), so in a list you derive the name from the item ID: view-transition-name: hero-${id}. Inline style with the dynamic value works.
the React pattern that’s actually working
In a React app, the trick is wrapping your route change in startViewTransition. Here's the pattern I've been using:
'use client';
import { useRouter } from 'next/navigation';export function useViewTransitionNavigate() {
const router = useRouter();
return (href: string) => {
if (!document.startViewTransition) {
router.push(href);
return;
}
document.startViewTransition(() => {
router.push(href);
});
};
}Then in your link components:
const navigate = useViewTransitionNavigate();
<button onClick={() => navigate(`/products/${product.id}`)}>View</button>That’s a same-document transition (you’re staying in the SPA, just changing routes). Works in every Baseline-supporting browser. Graceful fallback: in older browsers, the navigation just happens without animation. Nothing breaks.
For cross-document transitions (full page loads), you opt in with a CSS at-rule:
@view-transition {
navigation: auto;
}Drop that in your global stylesheet and Chrome / Safari will animate full-page navigations automatically. Firefox just does the navigation without animation. Progressive enhancement at its best.
the experimental React API, briefly
React has an experimental unstable_ViewTransition component that wraps the orchestration. The pitch is that it integrates with Suspense, lets you mark React-aware boundaries, and handles the race conditions between React's render cycle and the API.
It is, as the name suggests, unstable. I would not ship it in production. The pattern above (wrap your router.push in startViewTransition) gets you 90% of the way there with stable APIs. Save the React-integrated version for when it stabilizes.
what about Framer Motion
I have been thinking about this. The honest answer:
For page transitions, View Transitions has eaten Framer Motion’s lunch. You don’t need it anymore. Delete the AnimatePresence wrapper. Use startViewTransition. Your bundle drops by 50kb gzipped. Your transitions look better because they’re native.
For complex orchestrated animations within a component (gesture-driven UI, physics, drag-and-drop, intricate sequenced animations), Framer Motion still wins. The View Transitions API doesn’t do those things. It does layout-to-layout transitions, not freeform motion.
For CSS transitions / keyframe animations, you didn’t need Framer Motion in 2024 either. Stop reaching for it for things that are five lines of CSS.
The split I’d suggest: View Transitions for page/route changes and layout-driven shared element work. Framer Motion (if you need it at all) for interactive, gesture-y, in-component work. For a lot of teams that means Framer Motion goes away entirely, which is genuinely good for bundle size.
what’s still rough
Honest constraints to know going in:
Cross-document transitions in Firefox. Not there yet. Same-document is fine. If your app is an SPA, you’re set. If you’re doing full-page reloads between routes and want Firefox to animate them, you’re waiting.
The naming clash. view-transition-name must be unique per snapshot. If you have a grid of items and the user clicks one, the source thumbnail needs a unique name and the destination needs to match. Easy with templates. Easy to mess up the first time. Plan your name scheme.
Layout shift during the snapshot. If your page layout changes a lot during the transition (the new page has different padding, different scroll position, etc.), the animation can look weird. Test on real pages, not just demos.
Debugging is hard. When a transition doesn’t animate the way you expect, there’s not a great DevTools story yet. Chrome’s animation panel helps. You’ll still spend time on “why isn’t this morphing.” This will get better.
Z-index and stacking. During a transition, the browser creates a pseudo-element tree that can have surprising stacking. If you have fixed headers or overlays, test how they behave during the transition.
a real-world checklist
If you want to try this on a real app this week:
Pick one route transition that matters (probably your most-used navigation). Add view-transition-name to the shared element (image, title, card). Wrap the route change in startViewTransition. Ship it behind a flag. Watch it in Safari and Chrome. Celebrate.
Then start removing your Framer Motion route animations one by one. The replacement is shorter, faster, and more native-feeling.
If your app is content-heavy (blog, docs, marketing), add the @view-transition { navigation: auto; } rule globally and let cross-document transitions just happen. Free polish.
anyway
This is the kind of platform feature that quietly changes what’s possible on the web. Same as CSS variables in 2017, same as Grid in 2019. The first six months of “is this supported yet” are over. The next six months are the wave of apps that ship native-feeling transitions and don’t tell you they used the browser to do it. You can be one of them.
Spend an hour with it. Pick your one favorite navigation and animate it. You’ll feel the future a little bit, which is a rare experience on the web.
